    "summary": "Thutmose III, who ruled as co-pharaoh alongside [[event:1801|Hatshepsut]] until her death and then as sole ruler until approximately 1425 BC, conducted seventeen military campaigns into the Levant, Nubia, and Syria, transforming [[event:60|New Kingdom Egypt]] into the dominant military power of the Near East. He is often called the Napoleon of ancient Egypt for his strategic brilliance and the scale of his conquests.\n\nThe defining military achievement of Thutmose III was the [[event:1803|Battle of Megiddo]] in 1457 BC, where he led his army through the treacherous Aruna pass to catch a Canaanite coalition by surprise and besiege the city of Megiddo. Subsequent campaigns extended Egyptian control deep into Syria, bringing Egyptian armies into contact and conflict with the Mitanni kingdom. Thutmose III also pushed Egyptian power further south into Nubia, establishing administrative control over territories rich in gold, cattle, and trade goods.\n\nHis campaigns are documented in exceptional detail in the Annals inscribed on the walls of the Karnak Temple, one of the most valuable military records to survive from the ancient world. Thutmose III erected numerous obelisks, many of which were later transported to Rome, Constantinople, and other cities — including the Cleopatra's Needles now in London, New York, and Paris. His reign created an empire producing vast tributary wealth that funded a golden age of Egyptian culture.",
